<br>
It turns out this had repercussions in hell and was the reason it split into a triumverate.  I think it's in Hy Bender's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sandman</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> companion that Neil points out he was a bit hamstrung by DC continuity and had to treat Lucifer in the context of the triumverate, which wasn't originally his idea.<br>
<br>
Anyone else pick up the Jill Thompson <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Death: At Death's Door</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> manga story?  Great fun. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A> at: 10/3/03 2:12 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Mike Carey</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#FFFF99>(10/7/03 5:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   further ramifications</span><hr size=1> ...and then Garth Ennis had to create the First of the Fallen for Hellblazer because Lucifer was already taken by Sandman.  It was like ripples spreading out across...  you know...  everything.<br>
<br>
I still think Moore's run on Swamp Thing represents some of his best writing ever - but something changed when Swamp Thing left Earth, and some of those last few stories I felt were a little off.<br>
